
[1]sensible

   SENS'IBLE, a.

   1. Having the capacity of receiving impressions from external objects;
   capable of perceiving by the instrumentality of the proper organs. We
   say the body or the flesh is sensible, when it feels the impulse of an
   external body. It may be more or less sensible.

   2. Perceptible by the senses. The light of the moon furnishes no
   sensible heat.

   Air is sensible to the touch by its motion. Arbuthnot.

   3. Perceptible or perceived by the mind.

   The disgrace was more sensible then the pain. Temple.

   4. Perceiving or having perception, either by the mind or the senses.

   A man cannot think at any time, waking or sleeping, without being
   sensible of it.
